\begin_layout Section
Rough Sketch of the Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumers can move to a certain region with higher mobility and better income
 - and they can also stay in the same area and hope for unlikely mobility.
 We use a model to movement not for income but for mobility i.e.
 we consider an environment where mobility is not possible in an environment
 - while income could be higher or lower in the target location.
 The consumer households are dynasties in this setup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility the consumers gets is from overall maximisation of long-term
 asset values.
 There are no-status concerns other than accumulation of wealth i.e.
 status is interpreted only wealth accumulation in the long-term.
 Thus any status for the consumer is derived through the utility she gets
 from accumulated wealth.
 There are no status or positional concerns the consumers optimise other
 than assets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative income concerns mean that wealth matters less to the consumer
 in a poor area.
 So while consumers don't achieve status from money, their utility from
 wealth is different in poorer than it is in richer areas.
 There is no direct utility from income - instead the utility from wealth
 varies in the environment of varied probability of mobility.
 The area-wealth-level relative to which utility from wealth is higher or
 lower in an area is represented as the reference level 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j\in\mathscr{J}}$
\end_inset

 - where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{J}$
\end_inset

 is the set of areas.
 The probability of mobility is related with average wealth or the reference
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

 exogenously.
 The utility from assets in this variant of the model matters only with
 respect to the local reference 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer can therefore substitute moving to richer area with being
 relatively rich in a poorer area.
 The drop (see below) in utility by moving should still be there - since
 movement is not always possible - but the consumer also has the hope to
 move up because of local hierarchy.
\end_layout

