\begin_layout Standard
In the first-variant, we assume that consumers maximise overall assets subject
 to needs and would eventually reach an equilibrium where that consumer
 can no longer move to a richer place that provides higher income.
 The limitation to the places imposes a heavy cost (either to utility or
 to the money) - but there is always some place that is available to every
 consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the model is not a discrete one.
 Thus the choice of the movement for the consumer is continuous.
 In this first variant, the consumers optimise the total 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 assets without any relevance of a reference group.
 So there is no difference between utility from assets in the poorer or
 richer location.
 So there is no natural incentive to be in a poorer area - except a drop
 in utility or a rise in cost-function implied by constraints.
 There are pros and cons for cost-function rise and utility drop approaches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost-function is a more direct interpretation of constraints imposed
 by population limits or political stability but using it implies that an
 equivalent must be used for the second variant where reference point matters.
 On the other hand, the utility-drop has the advantage that it need not
 correspond to a constraint that must be shared with the second variant.
 For the same reason, it faces the criticism that it is only an indirect
 interpretation of population limits that utility from wealth must comply
 with.
\end_layout

